# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compute-shaders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:compute-shaders/compute-shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA is both a software layer that manages data, giving direct access to the GPU and CPU as necessary, and a library of APIs that enable parallel computation for various needs.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] In addition to drivers and runtime kernels, the CUDA platform includes compilers, libraries and developer tools to help programmers accelerate their applications.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA is written in the C programming language but is designed to work with a wide array of other programming languages including C++, Fortran, Python and Julia.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] This accessibility makes it easier for specialists in parallel programming to use GPU resources, in contrast to prior APIs like Direct3D and OpenGL, which require advanced skills in graphics programming.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA-powered GPUs also support programming frameworks such as OpenMP, OpenACC and OpenCL.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The graphics processing unit (GPU), as a specialized computer processor, addresses the demands of real-time high-resolution 3D graphics compute-intensive tasks.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] By 2012, GPUs had evolved into highly parallel multi-core systems allowing efficient manipulation of large blocks of data.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The origins of CUDA trace to the early 2000s, when Ian Buck, a computer science Ph.D. student at Stanford University, began experimenting with using GPUs for purposes beyond rendering graphics.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Buck had first become interested in GPUs during his undergraduate studies at Princeton University, initially through video gaming.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] After graduation, he interned at Nvidia, gaining deeper exposure to GPU architecture.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] At Stanford, he built an 8K gaming rig using 32 GeForce graphics cards, originally to push the limits of graphics performance in games like Quake and Doom.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] However, his interests shifted toward exploring the potential of GPUs for general-purpose parallel computing.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] To that end, Buck developed Brook, a programming language designed to enable general-purpose computing on GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] His work attracted support from both Nvidia and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] In 2004, Nvidia hired Buck and paired him with John Nickolls, the company's director of architecture for GPU computing.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Together, they began transforming Brook into what would become CUDA.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA was officially released by Nvidia in 2007.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Under the leadership of Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang, CUDA became central to the company's strategy of positioning GPUs as versatile hardware for scientific applications.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] By 2015, CUDA's development increasingly focused on accelerating machine learning and artificial neural network workloads.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The following table offers a non-exact description for the ontology of the CUDA framework.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The CUDA platform is accessible to software developers through CUDA-accelerated libraries, compiler directives such as OpenACC, and extensions to industry-standard programming languages including C, C++, Fortran and Python.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] C/C++ programmers can use 'CUDA C/C++', compiled to PTX with nvcc (Nvidia's LLVM-based C/C++ compiler) or by clang itself.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Fortran programmers can use 'CUDA Fortran', compiled with the PGI CUDA Fortran compiler from The Portland Group.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Python programmers can use the cuPyNumeric library to accelerate applications on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] In addition to libraries, compiler directives, CUDA C/C++ and CUDA Fortran, the CUDA platform supports other computational interfaces, including the Khronos Group's OpenCL, Microsoft's DirectCompute, OpenGL Compute Shader and C++ AMP.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Third party wrappers are also available for Python, Perl, Fortran, Java, Ruby, Lua, Common Lisp, Haskell, R, MATLAB, IDL, Julia, and native support in Mathematica.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] In the computer game industry, GPUs are used for graphics rendering, and for game physics calculations (physical effects such as debris, smoke, fire, fluids); examples include PhysX and Bullet.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA has also been used to accelerate non-graphical applications in computational biology, cryptography and other fields by an order of magnitude or more.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA provides both a low level API (CUDA **Driver** API, non single-source) and a higher level API (CUDA **Runtime** API, single-source).
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The initial CUDA SDK was made public on 15 February 2007, for Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Mac OS X support was later added in version 2.0, which supersedes the beta released February 14, 2008.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA works with all Nvidia GPUs from the G8x series onwards, including GeForce, Quadro and the Tesla line.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA is compatible with most standard operating systems.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Below is an example given in Python that computes the product of two arrays on the GPU.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The unofficial Python language bindings can be obtained from *PyCUDA*.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Additional Python bindings to simplify matrix multiplication operations can be found in the program *pycublas*.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Note on notation: compute capability X.Y is also written as SMXY or sm_XY (e.g.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] 10.3 as SM103 or sm_103) in professional Nvidia software and the code Nvidia has contributed to LLVM.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Note: CUDA SDK 10.2 is the last official release for macOS, as support will not be available for macOS in newer releases.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Note: A GPU with a higher compute capacity is able to execute PTX code meant for a GPU of a lower range of compute capacities.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] However, it is possible to compile CUDA code into a form that only works on one family (same "X") of GPUs; if existing code is compiled this way, recompilation will be needed for it to work on a newer GPU.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Note: Any missing lines or empty entries do reflect some lack of information on that exact item.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] For more information read the Nvidia CUDA C++ Programming Guide.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] CUDA competes with other GPU computing stacks: Intel OneAPI and AMD ROCm.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Whereas Nvidia's CUDA is closed-source, Intel's OneAPI and AMD's ROCm are open source.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] Originally made by Intel, other hardware adopters include Fujitsu and Huawei.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The goal is to offer open alternatives to Nvidia's CUDA.
[src:compute-shaders/cuda] The main companies behind it are Intel, Google, ARM, Qualcomm, Samsung, Imagination, and VMware.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:compute-shaders/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL is an open standard maintained by the Khronos Group, a non-profit, open standards organisation.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Conformant implementations (passed the Conformance Test Suite) are available from a range of companies including AMD, Arm, Cadence, Google, Imagination, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung, SPI and Verisilicon.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL views a computing system as consisting of a number of *compute devices*, which might be central processing units (CPUs) or "accelerators" such as graphics processing units (GPUs), attached to a *host* processor (a CPU).
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] It defines a C-like language for writing programs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Functions executed on an OpenCL device are called "kernels".
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] A single compute device typically consists of several *compute units*, which in turn comprise multiple *processing elements* (PEs).
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] A single kernel execution can run on all or many of the PEs in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In addition to its C-like programming language, OpenCL defines an application programming interface (API) that allows programs running on the host to launch kernels on the compute devices and manage device memory, which is (at least conceptually) separate from host memory.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Programs in the OpenCL language are intended to be compiled at run-time, so that OpenCL-using applications are portable between implementations for various host devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The OpenCL standard defines host APIs for C and C++; third-party APIs exist for other programming languages and platforms such as Python, Java, Perl, D and .NET.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] An implementation of the OpenCL standard consists of a library that implements the API for C and C++, and an OpenCL C compiler for the compute devices targeted.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In order to open the OpenCL programming model to other languages or to protect the kernel source from inspection, the Standard Portable Intermediate Representation (SPIR) can be used as a target-independent way to ship kernels between a front-end compiler and the OpenCL back-end.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] More recently Khronos Group has ratified SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source eDSL based on pure C++17 to improve programming productivity.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] People interested by C++ kernels but not in the SYCL single-source programming style can use C++ features with compute kernel sources written in "C++ for OpenCL" language.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Not every device needs to implement each level of this hierarchy in hardware.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Consistency between the various levels in the hierarchy is relaxed, and only enforced by explicit synchronization constructs, notably barriers.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Devices may or may not share memory with the host CPU.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The host API provides handles on device memory buffers and functions to transfer data back and forth between host and devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The programming language that is used to write compute kernels is called kernel language.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL adopts C/C++-based languages to specify the kernel computations performed on the device with some restrictions and additions to facilitate efficient mapping to the heterogeneous hardware resources of accelerators.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Traditionally OpenCL C was used to program the accelerators in OpenCL standard, later C++ for OpenCL kernel language was developed that inherited all functionality from OpenCL C but allowed to use C++ features in the kernel sources.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL C is a C99-based language dialect adapted to fit the device model in OpenCL.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Memory buffers reside in specific levels of the memory hierarchy, and pointers are annotated with the region qualifiers __global, __local, __constant, and __private, reflecting this.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Instead of a device program having a main function, OpenCL C functions are marked __kernel to signal that they are entry points into the program to be called from the host program.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Function pointers, bit fields and variable-length arrays are omitted, and recursion is forbidden.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The C standard library is replaced by a custom set of standard functions, geared toward math programming.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL C is extended to facilitate use of parallelism with vector types and operations, synchronization, and functions to work with work-items and work-groups.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Vectorized operations on these types are intended to map onto SIMD instructions sets, e.g., SSE or VMX, when running OpenCL programs on CPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Other specialized types include 2-d and 3-d image types.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The following is a matrix–vector multiplication algorithm in OpenCL C.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] To extend this into a full matrix–vector multiplication, the OpenCL runtime maps the kernel over the rows of the matrix.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On the host side, the clEnqueueNDRangeKernel function does this; it takes as arguments the kernel to execute, its arguments, and a number of work-items, corresponding to the number of rows in the matrix A.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This example will load a fast Fourier transform (FFT) implementation and execute it.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The code asks the OpenCL library for the first available graphics card, creates memory buffers for reading and writing (from the perspective of the graphics card), JIT-compiles the FFT-kernel and then finally asynchronously runs the kernel.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The result from the transform is not read in this example.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This is illustrative example code, not intended for serious use, so error-handling is entirely omitted.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] A full, open source implementation of an OpenCL FFT can be found on Apple's website.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL C++ is a short-lived specification for a language that combines OpenCL C and C++14.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] It was intended to be built in an *online mode* only, by passing the `-cl-std=c++` parameter in `clBuildProgram()`.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] No extension for detecting support for this language is described.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] It is unknown whether any driver actually supported this language.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In 2020, Khronos announced the transition to the community driven C++ for OpenCL programming language that provides features from C++17 in combination with the traditional OpenCL C features.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This language allows to leverage a rich variety of language features from standard C++ while preserving backward compatibility to OpenCL C.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This opens up a smooth transition path to C++ functionality for the OpenCL kernel code developers as they can continue using familiar programming flow and even tools as well as leverage existing extensions and libraries available for OpenCL C.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The language semantics is described in the documentation published in the releases of OpenCL-Docs repository hosted by the Khronos Group but it is currently not ratified by the Khronos Group.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The C++ for OpenCL language is not documented in a stand-alone document and it is based on the specification of C++ and OpenCL C.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The open source Clang compiler has supported C++ for OpenCL since release 9.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL has been originally developed as a Clang compiler extension and appeared in the release 9.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] As it was tightly coupled with OpenCL C and did not contain any Clang specific functionality its documentation has been re-hosted to the OpenCL-Docs repository from the Khronos Group along with the sources of other specifications and reference cards.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The first official release of this document describing C++ for OpenCL version 1.0 has been published in December 2020.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL 1.0 contains features from C++17 and it is backward compatible with OpenCL C 2.0.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In December 2021, a new provisional C++ for OpenCL version 2021 has been released which is fully compatible with the OpenCL 3.0 standard.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] A work in progress draft of the latest C++ for OpenCL documentation can be found on the Khronos website.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL supports most of the features (syntactically and semantically) from OpenCL C except for nested parallelism and blocks.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] However, there are minor differences in some supported features mainly related to differences in semantics between C++ and C.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] For example, C++ is more strict with the implicit type conversions and it does not support the restrict type qualifier.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The following C++ features are not supported by C++ for OpenCL: virtual functions, dynamic_cast operator, non-placement new/delete operators, exceptions, pointer to member functions, references to functions, C++ standard libraries.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL extends the concept of separate memory regions (*address spaces*) from OpenCL C to C++ features – functional casts, templates, class members, references, lambda functions, and operators.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Most of C++ features are not available for the kernel functions e.g. overloading or templating, arbitrary class layout in parameter type.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The following code snippet illustrates how kernels with complex-number arithmetic can be implemented in C++ for OpenCL language with convenient use of C++ features.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL language can be used for the same applications or libraries and in the same way as OpenCL C language is used.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Due to the rich variety of C++ language features, applications written in C++ for OpenCL can express complex functionality more conveniently than applications written in OpenCL C and in particular generic programming paradigm from C++ is very attractive to the library developers.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL sources can be compiled by OpenCL drivers that support *cl_ext_cxx_for_opencl* extension, which allows the use of `-cl-std=CLC++` in `clBuildProgram()`.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Arm has announced support for this extension in December 2020.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] However, due to increasing complexity of the algorithms accelerated on OpenCL devices, it is expected that more applications will compile C++ for OpenCL kernels offline using stand alone compilers such as Clang into executable binary format or portable binary format e.g.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Such an executable can be loaded during the OpenCL applications execution using a dedicated OpenCL API.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Binaries compiled from sources in C++ for OpenCL 1.0 can be executed on OpenCL 2.0 conformant devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Depending on the language features used in such kernel sources it can also be executed on devices supporting earlier OpenCL versions or OpenCL 3.0.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Aside from OpenCL drivers, kernels written in C++ for OpenCL can be compiled for execution on Vulkan devices using clspv compiler and clvk runtime layer, just the same way as OpenCL C kernels.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] C++ for OpenCL is an open language developed by the community of contributors listed in its documentation.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] New contributions to the language semantic definition or open source tooling support are accepted from anyone interested as soon as they are aligned with the main design philosophy and they are reviewed and approved by the experienced contributors.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL was initially developed by Apple Inc., which holds trademark rights, and refined into an initial proposal in collaboration with technical teams at AMD, IBM, Qualcomm, Intel, and Nvidia.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Apple submitted this initial proposal to the Khronos Group.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On June 16, 2008, the Khronos Compute Working Group was formed with representatives from CPU, GPU, embedded-processor, and software companies.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This group worked for five months to finish the technical details of the specification for OpenCL 1.0 by November 18, 2008.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This technical specification was reviewed by the Khronos members and approved for public release on December 8, 2008.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL 1.0 released with Mac OS X Snow Leopard on August 28, 2009.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] AMD decided to support OpenCL instead of the now deprecated Close to Metal in its Stream framework.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] RapidMind announced their adoption of OpenCL underneath their development platform to support GPUs from multiple vendors with one interface.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On December 9, 2008, Nvidia announced its intention to add full support for the OpenCL 1.0 specification to its GPU Computing Toolkit.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On October 30, 2009, IBM released its first OpenCL implementation as a part of the XL compilers.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Acceleration of calculations with factor to 1000 are possible with OpenCL in graphic cards against normal CPU.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Some important features of next Version of OpenCL are optional in 1.0 like double- or half-precision operations.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On November 15, 2011, the Khronos Group announced the OpenCL 1.2 specification, which added significant functionality over the previous versions in terms of performance and features for parallel programming.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] On November 18, 2013, the Khronos Group announced the ratification and public release of the finalized OpenCL 2.0 specification.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The ratification and release of the OpenCL 2.1 provisional specification was announced on March 3, 2015, at the Game Developer Conference in San Francisco.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] It introduced the OpenCL C++ kernel language, based on a subset of C++14, while maintaining support for the preexisting OpenCL C kernel language.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Vulkan and OpenCL 2.1 share SPIR-V as an intermediate representation allowing high-level language front-ends to share a common compilation target.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] AMD, ARM, Intel, HPC, and YetiWare have declared support for OpenCL 2.1.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL 2.2 brings the OpenCL C++ kernel language into the core specification for significantly enhanced parallel programming productivity.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Maintenance Update released in May 2018 with bugfixes.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The OpenCL 3.0 specification was released on September 30, 2020, after being in preview since April 2020.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL 1.2 functionality has become a mandatory baseline, while all OpenCL 2.x and OpenCL 3.0 features were made optional.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The specification retains the OpenCL C language and deprecates the OpenCL C++ Kernel Language, replacing it with the C++ for OpenCL language based on a Clang/LLVM compiler which implements a subset of C++17 and SPIR-V intermediate code.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 3.0.7 of C++ for OpenCL with some Khronos openCL extensions were presented at IWOCL 21.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual is 3.0.11 with some new extensions and corrections.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] NVIDIA, working closely with the Khronos OpenCL Working Group, improved Vulkan Interop with semaphores and memory sharing.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Last minor update was 3.0.14 with bugfix and a new extension for multiple devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] When releasing OpenCL 2.2, the Khronos Group announced that OpenCL would converge where possible with Vulkan to enable OpenCL software deployment flexibility over both APIs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This has been now demonstrated by Adobe's Premiere Rush using the clspv open source compiler to compile significant amounts of OpenCL C kernel code to run on a Vulkan runtime for deployment on Android.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL has a forward looking roadmap independent of Vulkan, with 'OpenCL Next' under development and targeting release in 2020.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL Next may integrate extensions such as Vulkan / OpenCL Interop, Scratch-Pad Memory Management, Extended Subgroups, SPIR-V 1.4 ingestion and SPIR-V Extended debug info.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL is also considering Vulkan-like loader and layers and a "flexible profile" for deployment flexibility on multiple accelerator types.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] OpenCL consists of a set of headers and a shared object that is loaded at runtime.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] An installable client driver (ICD) must be installed on the platform for every class of vendor for which the runtime would need to support.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] That is, for example, in order to support Nvidia devices on a Linux platform, the Nvidia ICD would need to be installed such that the OpenCL runtime (the ICD loader) would be able to locate the ICD for the vendor and redirect the calls appropriately.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The standard OpenCL header is used by the consumer application; calls to each function are then proxied by the OpenCL runtime to the appropriate driver using the ICD.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Each vendor must implement each OpenCL call in their driver.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The Apple, Nvidia, ROCm, RapidMind and Gallium3D implementations of OpenCL are all based on the LLVM Compiler technology and use the Clang compiler as their frontend.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Target complete OpenCL 1.0, 1.1 and 1.2 for AMD and Nvidia.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] New Target is modular OpenCL 3.0 with full support of OpenCL 1.2.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual state is available in Mesamatrix.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Image supports are here in the focus of development.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In Mesa 22.2 experimental implementation is available with openCL 3.0-support and image extension implementation for programs like Darktable.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Intel Xe (Arc) and AMD GCN+ are supported in Mesa 22.3+.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] AMD R600 and Nvidia Kepler+ are also target of hardware support.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] RustiCL outperform AMD ROCM with Radeon RX 6700 XT hardware at Luxmark Benchmark.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] In Mesa 23.2 support of important fp64 is at experimental level.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual Version 1.3.2 support OpenCL 1.2 complete (Ivy Bridge and higher) and OpenCL 2.0 optional for Skylake and newer.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] actual development targets: only support for 1.2 and 2.0, road to OpenCL 2.1, 2.2, 3.0 is gone to NEO.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This driver replaces Beignet implementation for supported platforms (not older 6.gen to Haswell).
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] NEO provides OpenCL 2.1 support on Core platforms and OpenCL 1.2 on Atom platforms.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual in 2020 also Graphic Gen 11 Ice Lake and Gen 12 Tiger Lake are supported.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] New OpenCL 3.0 is available for Alder Lake, Tiger Lake to Broadwell with Version 20.41+.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] It includes now optional OpenCL 2.0, 2.1 Features complete and some of 2.2.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] (Radeon Open Compute) is an open source Linux project built on OpenCL 1.2 with language support for 2.0.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The system is compatible with all modern AMD CPUs and APUs (actual partly GFX 7, GFX 8 and 9), as well as Intel Gen7.5+ CPUs (only with PCI 3.0).
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] With version 1.9 support is in some points extended experimental to Hardware with PCIe 2.0 and without atomics.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] An overview of actual work is done on XDC2018.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] ROCm Version 2.0 supports Full OpenCL 2.0, but some errors and limitations are on the todo list.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 3.10 was with improvements and new APIs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Announced at SC20 is ROCm 4.0 with support of AMD Compute Card Instinct MI 100.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual documentation of 5.5.1 and before is available at GitHub.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] RocM 5.5.x+ supports only GFX 9 Vega and later, so alternative are older RocM Releases or in future RustiCL for older Hardware.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] With version 1.0 OpenCL 1.2 was nearly fully implemented along with some 2.x features.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 1.2 is with LLVM/CLANG 6.0, 7.0 and Full OpenCL 1.2 support with all closed tickets in Milestone 1.2.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 1.5 implements LLVM/Clang 10 support.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 1.6 implements LLVM/Clang 11 support and CUDA Acceleration.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Actual targets are complete OpenCL 2.x, OpenCL 3.0 and improvement of performance.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] POCL 1.6 is with manual optimization at the same level of Intel compute runtime.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 1.7 implements LLVM/Clang 12 support and some new OpenCL 3.0 features.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 1.8 implements LLVM/Clang 13 support.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 3.0 implements OpenCL 3.0 at minimum level and LLVM/Clang 14.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Version 3.1 works with LLVM/Clang 15 and improved Spir-V support.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] An OpenCL implementation based on POCL by the NUDT researchers for Matrix-2000 was released in 2018.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The Matrix-2000 architecture is designed to replace the Intel Xeon Phi accelerators of the TianHe-2 supercomputer.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This programming framework is built on top of LLVM v5.0 and reuses some code pieces from POCL as well.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] To unlock the hardware potential, the device runtime uses a push-based task dispatching strategy and the performance of the kernel atomics is improved significantly.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] This framework has been deployed on the TH-2A system and is readily available to the public.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] Some of the software will next ported to improve POCL.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] As of 2016, OpenCL runs on graphics processing units (GPUs), CPUs with SIMD instructions, FPGAs, Movidius Myriad 2, Adapteva Epiphany and DSPs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] To be officially conformant, an implementation must pass the Khronos Conformance Test Suite (CTS), with results being submitted to the Khronos Adopters Program.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The Khronos CTS code for all OpenCL versions has been available in open source since 2017.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] The Khronos Group maintains an extended list of OpenCL-conformant products.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p01] All standard-conformant implementations can be queried using one of the clinfo tools (there are multiple tools with the same name and similar feature set).
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] It is possible to run any OpenCL kernel on any conformant implementation.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] However, performance of the kernel is not necessarily portable across platforms.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] Existing implementations have been shown to be competitive when kernel code is properly tuned, though, and auto-tuning has been suggested as a solution to the performance portability problem, yielding "acceptable levels of performance" in experimental linear algebra kernels.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] Portability of an entire application containing multiple kernels with differing behaviors was also studied, and shows that portability only required limited tradeoffs.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] A study at Delft University from 2011 that compared CUDA programs and their straightforward translation into OpenCL C found CUDA to outperform OpenCL by at most 30% on the Nvidia implementation.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] The researchers noted that their comparison could be made fairer by applying manual optimizations to the OpenCL programs, in which case there was "no reason for OpenCL to obtain worse performance than CUDA".
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] The performance differences could mostly be attributed to differences in the programming model (especially the memory model) and to NVIDIA's compiler optimizations for CUDA compared to those for OpenCL.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] Another study at D-Wave Systems Inc. found that "The OpenCL kernel’s performance is between about 13% and 63% slower, and the end-to-end time is between about 16% and 67% slower" than CUDA's performance.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] The fact that OpenCL allows workloads to be shared by CPU and GPU, executing the same programs, means that programmers can exploit both by dividing work among the devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] This leads to the problem of deciding how to partition the work, because the relative speeds of operations differ among the devices.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] Machine learning has been suggested to solve this problem: Grewe and O'Boyle describe a system of support-vector machines trained on compile-time features of program that can decide the device partitioning problem statically, without actually running the programs to measure their performance.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] In a comparison of actual graphic cards of AMD RDNA 2 and Nvidia RTX Series there is an undecided result by OpenCL-Tests.
[src:compute-shaders/opencl-p02] Possible performance increases from the use of Nvidia CUDA or OptiX were not tested.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:compute-shaders/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
